      {
        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "### Chemistry insight\nThe dominant species is the 1:1 Ni–EDTA complex (log K = 18.4), reflecting EDTA's exceptional hexadentate chelation of Ni²⁺. The protonated complex MHL (log K = 3.1 for the protonation step) is relevant near pH 3, while the hydroxo species M(OH)L only becomes significant at very high pH (log K = −11.9). The two networks differ mainly in ionic strength regime, with the higher-I network (ref_eq_net_5024) additionally including the MH₂L species (β_def_739) instead of the overall formation constant (β_def_812).\n\n*Source: NIST SRD-46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes)*",
